<br>
Well...if they truly are (I don't believe that yet), then /mourne.<br>
<br>
If they're not, /applaud VI programming.<br>
<br>
With respect to your petition, I was originally agreeing with the spirit, but not with the tactic.  Well, I'd have to say after some thought, yes, make it an AAXP or perhaps an inherent feature of bolt spells...similar to how wizards can crit.  (Not just mages, but anyone using a bolt, at any level, has a low percent chance to double).<br>
<br>
To those who are against this on the basis of its &quot;absurdity&quot; as &quot;double bolts were a bug&quot;, I present this to you:  Online games evolve.  What ships and what is played changes.  Even non-persistant games such as StarCraft have their inherent styles changed (Ever try to rush with Zerg at v1.00?  Try it post-Brood War...).  Games -evolve-.  I think it's safe to say that on the point that Raz makes: <br>
<br>
Doubles didn't severely unbalance the game<br>
<br>
....he's dead on.<br>
<br>
I think to extend on this observation, the game could evolve, be it as I suggest where bolts have an inherent chance for double, giving them a greater benefit and reason to be used (which compensates for their disadvantages compared to DD's) or through other mechanisms...and not limited to mages.<br>
<br>
Of course the fact that I support them probably should come as no surprise.  I use them, and am biased.  The fact that Raz does not use them yet supports their inclusion into the mage et al repertoire says something, for those with ears to listen.<br>
<br>
In other words...I think Raz did an excellent job (and is correct in his assesment) talking about how doubles -were- actually balanced enough to be included and embraced as a feature.  If you can get past the point of &quot;it's a bug, stupid&quot; and figure out that things are getting added all the time to the game, you might see that he's got a very valid point.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ut1ao.showPublicProfile?language=EN>T1AO</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#333333>(7/26/02 12:51:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=274.topic&index=65>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Comparing...</span><hr size=1> Balanz, I don't think the comparison to as how this relates to feign death is good. The feign death splitting a pull, is not a *bug*, feign death is supposed to lose aggro, be it 1 mob or 3. While verant may have never intended for a skill to be used a certain way, just because it is used that way does not mean it is a bug.<br>
Whereas double bolts were a *bug*, what seemed to be an act dealing with the z axis.<br>
Splitting a pull is a way of using feign death.<br>
Making a bolt hit twice is a numeric glitch dealing with the z axis.<br>
I wouldn't mind them bringing it back though, I mean, it takes knowledge to get those double bolts constantly. I have only ever gotten them once, when I was level 12 or so. But I don't think we should, it was a bug.<br>
And think of the uproar other classes would make if they brought back a bug for a class...<br>
Brilanya Elementweaver<br>
38th level Dark Elf Magician <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1668<br> <font color=#333333>(7/26/02 5:28:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=274.topic&index=69>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Double bolts exist in paper RPGs, not unheard of....</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Balanz you are getting into a &quot;Frenzied Protest&quot; about an issue that really does not exist<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->For an issue that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;does not exist,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> there is certainly a lot of emotion here.  Four pages of responses, and growing.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A Point of Pride does not come from exploiting the gaming engine<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->You mean like splitting pulls with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Feign Death</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which originally was considered an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;exploit&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and either was or was about to be removed from the game?  Or several of the techniques listed in <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.monkly-business.com/articles2.asp?ArticleNum=98">Laotzu's Guide to Advanced Pulling</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, incuding taking advantage of the fact the aggro is updated at ticks, giving a window of opportunity between ticks?<br>
<br>
Monks know the mechanics of the game quite well, and it is a point of pride their ability to push the limits of the game engine.  Whether these can be called bugs or exploits is a matter of opinion.<br>
<br>
Nonetheless, monks flourish in an environment of open discussion of the game mechanics and how best to apply them.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I, personally, am not entirely sure why Raz decided to post his petition.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->It's really quite simple.  I have always read the boards very carefully, and when I find a plausible opinion held by a fair number of mages, but which has not been put together into a single reasoned argument, I try to do that for them, even when it does not coincide precisely with my own.  As mentioned in my previous post, I did it on behalf of those who wanted pet penalties reduced, even though I prefered stronger neutral pets instead.<br>
<br>
Because there is no consensus among all mages, I try to identify distinct communities of consensus among us, and articulate those consensuses.  I often find I learn more when I try to see things from another person's point of view.<br>
<br>
I also feel that, like monks, we should not be afraid to discuss the details of games mechanics <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>openly</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, and how best to take advantage of them.  Knowing that double bolts were <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;nerfed&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> immediately following several open discussions of them in this forum, I felt obligated to respond on the behalf of those who mastered double bolts, and would mourn them.  If I let it simply pass with no comment and no effort, it would be another instance in favor of the attitude that we should only parade our weaknesses in public, like the pet haste cap, but avoid detailed discussion of our best tactics and strengths.<br>
<br>
I truly believe our best interests are served by open discussion, as monks have done.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Now when I consider how many double bolts I may have gotten that entire time, the risk (aggro), and how many spells would I have missed completely, I find that bolt spells are very underpowered. <br>
<br>
Why? In a group type battle, 1 or 2 bolts missed is a severe loss of mana efficiency and DPS.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is the core of my argument why double bolts are balanced, not a problem, and should be allowed to remain, at least in some form.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Balanz, I don't think the comparison to as how this relates to feign death is good.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Sadly, it is not good <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>enough</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  The comparison I am attempting to make here is that both are taking advantange of unintended consequences of game mechanics.  The problem is that how <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Feign Death</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> works is completely understood, whereas exactly how double bolts occur is unknown, perhaps even by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (who may simply have added code to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;plug the leak&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> without knowing how they occured).  All we know is that it has something to do with the way the z-axis is handled in an unexpected manner, since <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> EverQuest</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is not truly 3-D.<br>
<br>
The possibility of striking an opponent twice with the same bolt by exploiting positioning and local geometry is a feature of bolt spells in paper role playing games, such as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Dungeons and Dragons</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, so it is not as if this is completely unheard of.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> CONCLUSIONS:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The difficulty of using bolts and the cost of missing even one bolt begs for some compensating factor.  Up until the UI patch, some skilled mages could arrange for a chance of double bolts by taking advantage of geometry, just as in popular paper RPGs.  Making double bolts into a AA skill would make them unavailable for most working mages, who would find this unsatisfying.  Making it an innate property of bolts, with success based on dexterity or perhaps throwing skill would make it accessable to more mages, but would eliminate the skill involved in choosing appropriate geometry.<br>
<br>
I remain in favor of open discussion of all opinions and positions, and against both insults and secrecy.<br>
<br>
